The Autonomous Practices in particular start from the drive of the student, which is fuelled by passion, fascinations, discontent and sometimes even anger. They can function as very strong motors if you channel them well. The Autonomous Practices open up fields to critically engaged art and design students that they previously were able to explore in very limited ways. These fields can be seen as wastelands, in a positive sense. A wasteland may be overlooked, but it can be explored, it usually is full of potential and possibilities, something that can be built on and developed. However it is also rough territory; you need strong roots to survive.

Students of Autonomous Practices are able to picture these potentialities. We teach them to look beyond limitations and define practices that are not yet defined. Within these unknown territories they are able to mark their own little piece of turf and start building, to gradually turn it into something that can grow, take shape and become meaningful, for themselves and for others. To be able to do so, especially in the beginning of their careers, students require specific skills like critical thinking, inventiveness, self-organisation, perseverance and a healthy dose of stubbornness. Ability to collaborate is an aspect that needs to be mentioned specifically, as a key characteristic within Autonomous Practices, because in contrary to what the word ‘autonomous’ may imply, if you want to build something solid you have to do it collaboratively, together with others.

In art education in The Netherlands the word ‘autonomous’ has traditionally been designated to fine arts (in Dutch: ‘autonome beeldende kunst’). However we sensed strong needs of certain students working within other departments to work in autonomous ways as well. It’s not like this was never possible, but somehow it stayed limited within the ‘walls’ of the department. The Autonomous Practices open up to all disciplines, and bring autonomous makers together, focusing on developing their professional attitude and specialising in formulating their own artistic questions. This means students of all departments work together in groups. They learn from each other’s autonomous positions, collaborate and share each other’s ideas and knowledge. What happens when an advertiser, a graphic designer and a fine artist join forces? We don’t know, but we know it becomes exciting.

Within the Autonomous Practices students can specialise in four trajectories: Critical Studies, Digital Craft, Hacking and Public & Private. They roughly cover the fields an autonomous practitioner will operate in. They are intended to provide a framework for students to work with, not in any limiting way but in a way to be able to contextualise their work. These frameworks are not medium specific, students may choose their own means in which they want to express themselves. They are challenged to think of their work within these frameworks and develop it by formulating their own project proposals and research goals. Each trajectory offers specific courses, has tutors with related professional backgrounds and external partners to collaborate with.

Critical Studies are led by the question how you can give vital meaning to art and design in contemporary circumstances. You consult theoreticians and relate your findings to the works of prominent artists and designers. In collaboration with your peers, you display your documented insights in a public symposium, an expo, a performance and/or an intervention.

Digital Craft

Digital Craft has authorship and appropriation – the act of making something your own – at its core. Here, appropriation means not only reusing technologies, but also pushing them beyond standard use. The goal is to invent your own media with conceptual and technical rigour. As a digital craftsman, you will acquire and share concrete skills to work with both digital and analogue media; you will continuously refine your ideas, experiments, and techniques with a ‘can do’ ethos.

Hacking is finding

Hacking is finding applications that were not intended by the system’s maker. The subject primarily concerns the development of a mentality – how do you apply attributes or systems in a different way so as to bring about new or other objectives or effects.

Public & Private concentrates on interventions in national and international public space. These could be related to urban architecture, culture, the economy, virtual world, social or political issues, and to their increasing privatisation. The result can take any conceivable form: an image (sculpture, film, photo, billboard); a performance or a virtual piece of work. It may as well trigger a social process or way of thinking.

Today’s world faces big challenges, the vast scale of them becomes difficult to comprehend. Issues like politics, economics, migration or environment become abstractions almost, this is how they are getting addressed, big problems need even bigger solutions. This increase in scale is also noticeable in our social behaviour. As people we tend to operate within ever expanding networks. The growing role of technology in our lives has made this much easier, but also more complex and confusing. Autonomous makers are able to critically engage with these tendencies, to not take them for granted and most importantly, to bring them back to a personal level. They are able to come up with intelligent and practical responses, to break systems, find loopholes, appropriate, and make things their own. They can deploy new strategies to intervene and get their messages across. Autonomous practices are critically driven, self-organised and bottom up, always starting from a personal engagement.

The biological computer by Emma van der Leest

Commercial Practice – minor: Innovation, Engineering and Design (IPO)

Form Follows Organism: the biological computer’ is a project about biodesign and the shifting role of the (product) designer. Biodesign is based on the principles of biofabrication, a field that emerged out of regenerative medicine technologies. Biodesign incorporates living organisms e.g. bacteria, fungi, algae or cells into the design process. Form Follows organism is about applying design knowledge in consumer products and design methodologies. Asking ‘how can we control the process of growing materials or products?’ And ‘how can we design new tools and algorithms that unlock the power of living cells?’

Emma co-created with a yellow intelligent slime mould, to find out if she can use an organism to create smart patterns and designs, based on the biological algorithm. Her product is a new design paradigm, centered on cultivating materials with living cells who are cultured and engineered to synthesize natures materials but with new functional and aesthetic properties.

This project was nominated for the 2015 Drempel award.

Keywords: Biodesign, design, living organanism, biological alogorithm, biomaterials, cells,

A research project about the Dutch shrimp and its industry

Jade Ruijzenaars
BA Lifestyle Design, minor New Frontiers
www.jaderuijzenaars.nl

Crangon Crangon, a story of Dutch shrimp.
Freshly caught Dutch shrimps are usually sent to Morocco for peeling, due to lower labour costs in the region. Once processed, the peeled shrimp are trucked back to Europe for consumption. Their empty shells – 70% of the total volume – remain in Morocco.

Recently a large automated peeling centre was opened in Groningen resulting in a never before seen, yet significant amount of shrimp waste in the Netherlands.

This triggered Jade Ruijzenaars to explore the world of the Dutch shrimp. Through material experimentation she discovered a new application for the otherwise ‘useless’ shrimp shells in ceramic glaze.

Her journey ventured deep into the chemistry and biology of shrimp shells and the valuable substances that can be extracted from them. Her cabinet includes practical design research and shows how a material that is usually perceived as waste, can be used in a wide range of applications.

Keywords: Dutch shrimp, material research, experiment, production chains,

content.rendered:
The Commercial Practices are oriented towards our “next economy”. Our world is changing rapidly fused for example by technological disruptive innovations. This changing world creates new opportunities and roles for prospective designers and artists.

Creative input has never been so important within businesses as today. In order to develop new ways to create economic value, spot potentially untapped markets and come up with designs, products and services that are sustainable and make a difference, the designer/ artist is becoming an increasingly key player in achieving these goals.

The key feature of being a commercial practitioner is that you take the market as your point of departure. Research into target groups is key before concept development and visualization takes place. It is important that the concept, service, or product adds value for the company, platform or consumer(s).

These characteristics of a commercial practitioner relate and embed themselves in the Majors of the Willem de Kooning Academy. Some majors are already commercially oriented. For example Advertising, Fashion and Lifestyle all take consumers (market) as a starting point. These disciplines are all influenced greatly by our “next economy”. The way we advertise for example is changing and the meaning of Fashion and its role on the environment is being scrutinized. Lifestyle focuses on how we as individuals or groups are being transformed by the world we live in. What are the future behaviors and needs of new upcoming communities?

Within the Commercial Practice we can distinguish four urgent topics that are put forward in the current curriculum. New Frontiers challenges you to experiment, create connections and push the boundaries. You develop new ways of thinking and acting in innovative processes. What are the new markets, products or services of the future?

The time in which Branding was seen as merely developing a logo or brand, visual identity, advertising and/or marketing is long gone. Branding is so much more. It is about values, needs, ways of life, identities, expression and trust. And it is not – as is thought by many policy makers – a ‘soft issue’. Instead, it is the basis of quality of life. Partly as a result of the influence of ‘the new critical consumer’, brands are no longer primarily influenced by the masses, but sooner by the individual: by ‘you and me’. A designer or artist facilitates this belief by giving this influence visual form in an authentic manner. Within Branding it is important to look at what it might be for example 30 years from now.

Data Design is connected to current developments such as open data and big data. What is the meaning of data and how is its importance increasing within our ever increasing digital world? In this minor you learn to react on data in a conceptual, enquiring and visual way. You learn to recognize the various types of data and to work with them by examining them thoroughly, using visual research methods. You also learn to use various tools so that you can design dynamic data.

In Service Design our premise is that the design approach is of great value for setting up and designing – and the success – of services. Here you are confronted with the ‘wicked problems’ that go together with the design of services. Service Design offers you, as a designer, the insights, knowledge and the tools to be at the forefront of new, pioneering concepts of service provision. Service Design is becoming increasingly important in our world where consumers are increasingly getting used to having their needs met by a push of a button.

Eventually Graduates of the Commercial Practice are innovators, prepared to work in our ever changing world as “creative pioneers”, finding new ways and solutions by thinking “out of the box”. Graduates will have the experience of working with bigger and smaller companies, from their own area of expertise, that have the common goal to create added value for their market and customers. Graduates will know how to work together and use each other’s assets to create something great. They are the next generation of creatives that will rise up to the challenge.
